    what is a deadlock in os | Introduction of Deadlock in Operating System | define deadlock

       1.🥲 🧠 Deadlock in Operating System

           A deadlock is a situation where a group of processes are blocked forever, each waiting for a resource held by another process.

           🔄 Example:
              Process P1 holds Resource A and waits for B
              Process P2 holds Resource B and waits for A
              
              👉 Both wait forever → deadlock


      2.😣 deadlock characterization part 1 | necessary conditions for deadlock       

            1. Mutual Exclusion
                Resource can be used by only one process at a time

            2. Hold and Wait
               Process holds one resource and waits for another 

            3. No Preemption
                 Resource cannot be taken away forcefully  

            4. Circular Wait
                Processes form a cycle, each waiting for next  


        3.😙 deadlock prevention in os | deadlock prevention in operating system  

             1. ❌ Mutual Exclusion (reduce if possible)
                 Use sharable resources where possible       

             2. ❌ Hold and Wait
                  Process must request all resources at once   

             3. ❌ No Preemption
                 Take resource away if process is waiting  

             4. ❌ Circular Wait
                 Assign order to resources and request in that order         

         ⚠️ Drawback:
            May lead to low resource utilization
            Processes may wait longer                  